# Coracoacromial Ligament

> The **coracoacromial ligament** spans between the [[Coracoid Process]] and the [[Acromion]], forming the **coracoacromial arch** — a rigid roof that prevents superior humeral head escape but also compresses the subacromial space.

## 🔗 Key Connections
- **Origin** — Lateral [[Coracoid Process]]
- **Insertion** — Anterior-inferior [[Acromion]]
- **Forms** — Coracoacromial arch (with acromion and coracoid)
- **Contents below arch** — Supraspinatus tendon, subacromial bursa, biceps tendon (long head)

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Subacromial impingement** — Coracoacromial arch compresses supraspinatus tendon between it and the humeral head → pain on elevation
- **Rotator cuff tear** — Progressive abrasion from arch leads to supraspinatus tears
- **Subacromial decompression (SAD)** — Acromioplasty may include CA ligament release to expand subacromial space
- **Acromial morphology** — Type III (hooked) acromion + tight CA ligament = highest impingement risk

